tr:researchMaterialOutputs><gtr:researchMaterialOutput><gtr:description>There are a number of difficulties with modeling arbovirus infections in mice. These include; an inability of many human arboviruses to replicate in the presence of a functioning type I IFN system; an inability of virus to disseminate from inoculation sites to the blood and distal tissues; the absence of sophisticated molecular tools for easily generating genetically modified viral strains; and the use of virus stock derived from mammalian cells that lack many of the glycosylation-motifs that virus derived from mosquito cells exhibit. We have developed a new in vivo model system that makes use of Semliki Forest virus (SFV), an alphavirus that is a close relative of the chikungunya virus. SFV infects and disseminates within both wild type mice and mosquitoes and exists in both virulent, avirulent forms and transgenic. SFV4 is an avirulent strain that rarely triggers clinical disease, whilst SFV L10 is highly virulent causing lethal encephalitis within a week. In these studies, viruses were grown in Aedes cell culture and sub ?l volumes injected into mice, to replicate delivery of virus by the natural vector, either in the absence or presence of Aedes aegypti mosquito bites. Thus, this model mimics the most relevant aspects of natural infection by arboviruses and enables the reductive study of the complex interactions between mosquito, viral and host factors.</gtr:description><gtr:id>7D335805-7905-4080-A7CD-29A1807AAD37</gtr:id><gtr:impact>This model mimics the most relevant aspects of natural infection by arboviruses and enables the reductive study of the complex interactions between mosquito, viral and host factors. We aim to submit several manuscripts to high impact journals in the near future.</gtr:impact><gtr:providedToOthers>false</gtr:providedToOthers><gtr:title>Novel in vivo model for studying mosquito-borne viral disease</gtr:title><gtr:type>Model of mechanisms or symptoms - mammalian in 